


1. du -ch ~       # show the total space used by location in linux os in human readsble format

2. tree ~          # display the ~ directory in nice tree structure. This is nor installed in ubuntu by default, 
                      but though it is not recomended thats why its not instaled in ubuntu by default but it 
                      will be a very good resource for learning porpose so use it.

3. journalctl -g <pattern>   # grep for pattern in journalctl
4. journalctl -f    # follow the logs

5. grep -v <pattern>    # inverts the selection on the pattern i.e matches anything tha is not in the <pattern>
